By 1990, 75% of Americans favored placing term limits on elected
officials.  Some believed limits were constitutional and would make
the legislatures more responsive.  Others believed limits were not
supported by the founding fathers and would only give power to
lobbyists, staffs, and bureaucrats.  Some writers suggested other
solutions.</SUM>
